The substance of his lecture as given by Xenophon in the well-known ‘Choice ol Hercules’ was this: “When Hercules, entering upon manhood, was on the point of choosing between virtue and vice, two women appeared to him, the one of dignified beauty, purity, modesty, and discretion, the other of a voluptuous form and meretricious look and dress. The latter promised to lead him by the shortest road, without any toll, to the enjoyment of every pleasure. The other, while she reminded him os his ancestors and his noble nature, did not conceal from him that the gods have granted nothing really beautiful and good without trouble or pain· Hercules decided in favour of virtue. The episode has been paraphrased in English verse by Shen· stone, and by Bishop Louth, and'there is a prose translation of it in the ‘Tatler' No. 97. Allusions to it are frequent in classical writers, eg. Sil. Ital. Punic. xv 18-127, Lucian Somn. c. 6, Deor. dialog. xx rr, Her- motimus c. 25.
